defaultInformation on defaultthe definition ofdefault a regulatory function for the purposes of clauses 58 to 61 of the Draft Deregulation Billdefault&#xa0;default&#xa0;
defaultClause 61 of the Draft Deregulation Bill defines a regulatory function to which the duty to have regard to the des
defaultirability of economic growth can apply.  It states:
default&#xa0;
default“ 61 Sections 58 to 60: interpretationdefault(1) In sections 58 to 60, “regulatory function” means:
default(a) a function under or by virtue of an Act or subordinate legislation of
defaultimposing requirements, restrictions or conditions, or setting standards
defaultor giving guidance, in relation to an activity; or
default(b) a function which relates to the securing of compliance with, or the
defaultenforcement of, requirements, restrictions, conditions, standards or
defaultguidance which, under or by virtue of an Act or subordinate legislation,
defaultrelate to an activity.
default&#xa0;
default(2) 
default              
defaultIn subsection (1)(a) and (b) the references to a function include a function
defaultexercisable by or on behalf of the Crown.
default&#xa0;
default(3) In subsection (1)(a) and (b) the references to an activity include:
default(a) providing goods and services; and
default(b) employing or offering employment to a person.
default&#xa0;
default(4) 
default              
defaultIn sections 59 and 60, “Minister of the Crown” has the same meaning as in the Ministers of the Crown Act 1975.
default&#xa0;
default(5) 
default              
defaultIn this section, “subordinate legislation” has the same meaning as in the
defaultInterpretation Act 1978.
default 
default” 
default&#xa0;
defaultThis definition has been adopted to ensure 
defaultthat 
defaultthe policy objectives are achieved and 
defaultthat 
defaultthe duty to have regard to growth is 
defaultapplied 
defaultto 
defaultall 
defaultregulator
defaulty functions to which it would be appropriate. It is also consistent with the existing definition that underpins the statutory code of practice for regulators (Regulators’ Compliance Code). The definition above does not expressly exclude economic regulatory functions; however the Government is clear that this duty is designed to apply to non-economic regulatory functions, rather than economic regulatory functions.
default&#xa0;defaultEconomic rdefaultegulatory functionsdefault&#xa0;
defaultIn the 
defaultUK
default, economic regulation has typically been introduced in areas where network effects and/or economies of scale create circumstances - such as natural monopolies – which limit the prospects for effective competition. 
defaultThe aim of economic regulation is to create a system of incentives and penalties that replicate the outcomes of competition in terms of consumer prices, quality and investment and puts the protection of consumers’ interests at its heart. 
defaultTypically, economic regulators oversee infrastructure sectors such as gas and electricity (Ofgem), Water (Ofwat) and Communications (Ofcom). Economic regulation in these sectors caps the prices that dominant companies can charge in order to promote efficiency and fairness, while providing them a return on their assets and investments. 
defaultEconomic regulation has also been applied to non-infrastructure sectors where similar institutional arrangements apply, such as the future economic regulation of healthcare services (Monitor).
defaultEconomic regulation is a qualitatively different form of regulation to non-economic regulation (such as that undertaken by regulators such as the Health and Safety Executive or the Environment Agency) which do 
defaultnot defaultcorrect for the market failure of natural monopoly 
defaultor defaultpromote efficiency within a market. 
defaultHowever t
defaulthe distinction is not absolute. There are some bodies that conduct a mix of both economic and non-economic regulatory functions (for example safety), such as the Civil Aviation Authority. Government is clear that it aims to ensure that as wide a range of non-economic regulatory functions 
defaultas possible are
default captured as part of the 
defaultgr
defaultowth 
defaultd
defaultuty. It therefore is seeking to apply the 
defaultg
defaultrowth 
defaultd
defaultuty to the non-economic regulatory functions of such bodies, where the level of non-economic regulatory activity is significant.
